<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-21T16:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-21T16:45:00-05:00" n="947" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d947">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00 Bandit Activities, 1931/241:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Beaulac</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-21T16:00:00-05:45">September 21, 1931—4
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 8:33 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>173. My 167, September 18, 3 p.m. The Acting Jefe Director of the Guardia
                            has informed me that no death sentences were applied in the case of the
                            rioters at Rama. I have discussed with him the Department’s attitude
                            concerning the trial of civilians and Guardia courts martial and he will
                            take measures to see that such trials are not held in the future.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Beaulac</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>